Message JSON: {"userId":"d194a01e-23a8-40b5-8926-68343b6c20da","text":"how does the shot work"}

Text: The shot is a type of birth control that you get every 3 months to prevent pregnancy. It’s technically called DepoProvera and it works by preventing ovulation (when your body releases an egg) - no egg, no baby! If you don’t mind getting a quick prick every 3 months, you should definitely talk to your doctor about getting it.

Text: how does the implant work
Message JSON: {"userId":"d194a01e-23a8-40b5-8926-68343b6c20da","text":"how does the implant work"}

Text: The implant is a type of birth control that goes into your upper arm to prevent pregnancy. It used to be called Implanon but now it’s called Nexplanon. It’s a teeny rod that releases progestin to stop ovulation (no egg, no baby) and thickens mucus in your cervix.
